dertaken on the Enterprise Management Incentives exemptions and reliefs; and if he will place a copy of that equality impact assessment in the Library.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","170669"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968287","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-09-10","<p>​We are deeply concerned by this crisis, which is self inflicted and has caused huge pressure on the region. I spoke on 6 September with the Peruvian Foreign Minister, Nestor Popolizio, to discuss the situation, to receive an update on the recent Andean Community (Peru, Colombia and Ecuador) meeting in Lima, and on the Ecuador-convened &quot;regional technical meeting&quot; on Venezuela that took place in Quito on 3-4 September to discuss the migration crisis. The Foreign Secretary also discussed the crisis with the Colombian Foreign Minister in New York on 24 August.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-09-10T15:40:07.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968287/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968287/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968287/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-09-05","Venezuela: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he had had with his Latin American counterparts on their response to Venezuelan refugees.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","170730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968288","Treasury","false","2018-09-14","<p>HMRC published a research report <em>Evaluation of enterprise Management Scheme incentives </em>in June 2018. This presents evidence on a number of economic and distributional issues.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/716544/EMI_report_Final.pdf" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/716544/EMI_report_Final.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>HMRC carefully considers the equality impacts of all decisions on those sharing protected characteristics as stipulated by the ‘Public Sector Equality Duty’, including gender, race and disability - in line with both its legal obligations and with its strong commitment to equality issues. An equality impact assessment was included in the Tax Information and Impacts Note (TIIN) published on 9 December 2015 which is published here:</p><p><a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20170525152716/https:/www.gov.uk/government/publications/employee-share-schemes-simplification-of-the-rules/employee-share-schemes-simplification-of-the-rules" target="_blank">http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20170525152716/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/employee-share-schemes-simplification-of-the-rules/employee-share-schemes-simplification-of-the-rules</a></p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","170666 ; 170669","2018-09-14T09:36:06.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968288/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968288/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968288/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-05","Enterprise Management Incentives","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department has identified a disproportionate effect of Enterprise Management Incentives exemptions and reliefs with regard to gender and other protected characteristics under the Equality Act 2010.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","170670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968289","Treasury","false","2018-09-13","<p>The Government has published its White Paper on the future relationship, which is our vision for a bold, ambitious and innovative new partnership with the EU.</p><p> </p><p>The Government remains confident the UK and EU will agree a mutually advantageous deal. Leaving the EU without a deal is in neither side’s interests.</p><p> </p><p>Once the Government has agreed a deal with the EU we will provide Parliament with the appropriate analysis of that deal ahead of the vote on the final deal.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen","170674 ; 170675 ; 170676 ; 170677","2018-09-13T09:11:07.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968289/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968289/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968289/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-05","National Income","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the loss of tax revenue in the event of a GDP fall of 7.7 per cent over (a) five years, (b) 10 years and (c) 15 years; and if he will place a copy of the findings in the Library.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","170671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968290","Treasury","false","2018-09-10","<p>HMRC aims to respond to 80% of correspondence within 15 working days and answer telephone calls within an average time of 5 minutes.</p><p>Since 6 April 2018, 95.65% of new Inheritance Tax accounts submitted to HMRC are processed within 15 working days. This enables the customer to obtain Grant of Representation.</p><p>If compliance checks are required, then HMRC will write to the customer and provide them with a timeline and a date indicating how long the checks will take.</p><p>For the week ending 31 August 2018, HMRC responded to 66.38% of inheritance tax post within 15 working days. We answered the phone within an average of 5 minutes</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-09-10T16:40:53.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968290/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968290/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968290/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-05","Revenue and Customs: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the average amount of time is for a person to receive a response from HMRC caseworkers for queries on (a) inheritance tax payments and (b) other subjects; and whether his Department has any target times for such responses to be sent.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","170734"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968291","Treasury","false","2018-09-14","<p>The government remains confident of concluding a deal with the EU and firmly believes that this deal will genuinely work for everyone across the UK.</p><p> </p><p>HM Treasury carefully considers equality impacts on those sharing protected characteristics, including gender, race and disability on an ongoing basis - in line with both its legal obligations and with its strong commitment to equality issues.</p><p> </p><p>As the department with overall responsibility for leaving the EU it is for the Department for Exiting the EU to provide information on any overall disproportionate effect on those with protected characteristics</p>","Salisbury","John Glen","170673","2018-09-14T11:41:55.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968291/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968291/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968291/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-05","Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what equality impact assessment on gender and other protected characteristics under the Equality Act 2010 his Department has undertaken with regard to the UK leaving the EU without a deal; and if he will place a copy of that equality impact assessment in the Library.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","170672"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968292","Treasury","false","2018-09-14","<p>The government remains confident of concluding a deal with the EU and firmly believes that this deal will genuinely work for everyone across the UK.</p><p> </p><p>HM Treasury carefully considers equality impacts on those sharing protected characteristics, including gender, race and disability on an ongoing basis - in line with both its legal obligations and with its strong commitment to equality issues.</p><p> </p><p>As the department with overall responsibility for leaving the EU it is for the Department for Exiting the EU to provide information on any overall disproportionate effect on those with protected characteristics</p>","Salisbury","John Glen","170672","2018-09-14T11:41:55.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968292/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968292/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968292/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-05","Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department has identified a disproportionate effect of the UK leaving the EU without a deal with regard to gender and other protected characteristics under the Equality Act 2010.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","170673"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968294","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-09-10","<p>Experimental badging is used so that users and stakeholders can be involved in the assessment of the publications’ suitability and quality while it is being developed. We are still expanding the Child Maintenance Service Publication and will be performing a full review of our overall Child Maintenance publication strategy over the next 6 months in the light of the completion of the Child Support Agency case closure process.</p><p> </p><p>Once those changes are complete we plan to release Child Maintenance Service statistics under standard Official Statistics guidelines in 2019.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2018-09-10T16:03:19.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968294/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968294/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968294/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-09-05","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the timescale is for removing the experimental status of quarterly Child Maintenance Service statistics.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","170879"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968295","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-09-10","<p>Significant progress has been made in designing a new approach to the delivery of data analytical platforms. This has been successfully deployed in Universal Credit with work underway in Pensions and Finance.</p><p> </p><p>Development of the new Data and Analytics platform for Children was originally planned to complete in late 2017 but was delayed. However, transformation has now begun of the current 2012 Data Warehouse to this new platform and we expect to complete this work in 2020.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-09-10T15:28:27.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968295/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968295/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968295/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-09-05","Department for Work and Pensions: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the paper, Strategy for the publication of information about the 2012 scheme, updated 30 November 2016, whether the Data Warehouse has been replaced by the new Data and Analytics Platform.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","170880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968296","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-09-10","<p>Information on fees in the financial year to date will not be available until audit of the 2017/18 Client Funds Account has been completed.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2018-09-10T16:15:38.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968296/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968296/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968296/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-09-05","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the monthly receipts accrued to the public purse were from (a) the fee charged for applications to the Child Maintenance Service (CMS), (b) the collection fee for paying parents using the CMS Collect and Pay service, (c) the collection fee for receiving parents using the CMS Collect and Pay service and (d) enforcement fees levied on paying parents in each month since March 2017.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","170881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968297","Department for Work and Pensions","true","2018-09-10","<p><del class="ministerial">We are not able to provide details of estimates for receipts to the public purse from Child Maintenance Service charges for 2019-20 and 2020-21 as these figures will comprise part of the Spending Review which has yet to be agreed.</del><ins class="ministerial">Details of estimates for receipts to the public purse from Child Maintenance Service charges are not yet available. We expect to have estimates for 2019-20 early in 2019. Estimates for 2020-21 will form part of the next Spending Review.</ins></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2018-09-10T16:19:10.747Z","2018-10-18T10:07:58.293Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968297/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968297/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968297/answer","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968297/answer/previousversion/74187","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-09-05","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate she has made of the money that will accrue to the public purse of the (a) fee charged for applications to the Child Maintenance Service (CMS), (b) collection fee for paying parents using the CMS Collect and Pay service, (c) collection fee for receiving parents using the CMS Collect and Pay service and (d) enforcement fees levied on paying parents in (i) 2019-20 and (ii) 2020-21.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","170882"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968299","Home Office","false","2018-09-10","<p>The GLAA has a full time equivalent of 51.4 staff who are responsible for frontline inspection activity, of whom the full time equivalent of 15.3 are female.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-09-10T16:17:01.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968299/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968299/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968299/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-09-05","Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority: Inspections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many of the Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority staff responsible for frontline inspection activity are female.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","170883"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968300","Home Office","false","2018-09-10","<p>The Department does not provide training to Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority (GLAA) frontline inspection officials on these matters. The GLAA is responsible for training its staff.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-09-10T16:20:09.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968300/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968300/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968300/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-09-05","Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority: Inspections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what training he Department has provided to Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority frontline inspection officials on the (a) identification of indicators of gender based violence and (b) harassment at work.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","170884"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968301","Home Office","false","2018-09-26","<p>Information is not collected by the Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority in the form requested. All intelligence reports received are reviewed by GLAA. The next step after review of an intelligence report is dependent upon the content of the report. Some intelligence reports are sufficient to trigger investigative or inspection activity – these reports are described as “actionable”. Other intelligence reports may add to an existing intelligence picture and may contribute to future action. Some intelligence reports duplicate information previously received.</p><p>The table sets out the total number of intelligence reports received by the GLAA in the years 2015-16 to 2017-18 and the number of such reports that were actionable:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>a) Year</p></td><td><p>b) Intelligence Reports Received</p></td><td><p>c) Number of reports at b) that were actionable</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>4,240</p></td><td><p>928</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>2,847</p></td><td><p>630</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017-18</p></td><td><p>3,987</p></td><td><p>908</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-09-26T12:08:06.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968301/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968301/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968301/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-09-05","Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many external intelligence reports received by the Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority from non-governmental organisations were (a) received and (b) acted upon in (i) 2015-16, (ii) 2016-17 and (ii) 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","170885"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968302","Home Office","false","2018-09-10","<p>Tier 1 interventions involve action by the Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority (GLAA) to recover, for workers, money owed to them by employers. Recovery involves payment of the sums owed by the employers direct to the workers concerned, not to the public purse. The amounts recovered for workers in this way are published annually in the GLAA’s Annual Report and Accounts.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-09-10T16:16:08.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968302/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968302/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968302/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-09-05","Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much money has been accrued to the public purse as a result of Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority Tier 1 interventions in each of the last six months.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","170886"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968303","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-09-10","<p>We are currently carefully considering the findings and recommendations made in the Child Migration Programmes report by the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse (IICSA) and will respond in due course.</p><p> </p><p>We are aware of the age and declining health of many former child migrants, and we are committed to providing a considered response to all of the Inquiry's recommendations. The Home Office leads on the Government's response to the IICSA Interim Report.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","170897","2018-09-10T15:58:46.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968303/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968303/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968303/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-09-05","Child Sexual Abuse Independent Panel Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, when he plans to publish the Government's response to the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse's report on Child Migrant Programmes, published on 1 March 2018.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","170887"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968304","Home Office","false","2018-09-10","<p>The UK’s resettlement programmes follow the humanitarian principles of impartiality and neutrality, which means that we resettle solely based on needs identified by UNHCR through their established processes, rather than on the basis of ethno-religious origin.</p><p>We believe that one way to protect the privacy of those being resettled and support their recovery and integration is to limit the amount of information about them that we make publicly available.</p><p>We therefore do not routinely publish a religious and ethnic breakdown of those who have been resettled, however internal management information indicates that the majority of Syrian refugees referred by UNHCR, and resettled to the UK are Muslim, with Christians and other religious groups represented in smaller numbers.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-09-10T16:28:38.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968304/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968304/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968304/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-09-05","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many Syrian refugees of each religious group his Department has (a) recommended to be resettled by the UN; and (b) agreed to resettle in the UK in each quarter of each of the last four years.","false","Biography information for Preet Kaur Gill","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Preet Kaur Gill","170888"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968305","Department for International Development","false","2018-09-10","<p>DFID is committed to taking a comprehensive approach to mental health.</p><p> </p><p>This includes working to improve the provision, equity and quality of mental health services. For example, in Ghana our Health Sector Support Programme has supported mental health systems strengthening and efforts to address underlying stigma and discrimination.</p><p> </p><p>Through Education Cannot Wait, the UK is funding safe learning spaces, teaching materials and psycho-social support – which aims to ensure 50% of qualified teachers in crises are fully trained in psychosocial support.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-09-10T17:04:15.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968305/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968305/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968305/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-09-05","Africa: Mental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to improve mental health (a) care and (b) education in Africa.","false","Biography information for Preet Kaur Gill","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Preet Kaur Gill","170889"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968307","Treasury","false","2018-09-13","<p>The Government has published its White Paper on the future relationship, which is our vision for a bold, ambitious and innovative new partnership with the EU.</p><p> </p><p>The Government remains confident the UK and EU will agree a mutually advantageous deal. Leaving the EU without a deal is in neither side’s interests.</p><p> </p><p>Once the Government has agreed a deal with the EU we will provide Parliament with the appropriate analysis of that deal ahead of the vote on the final deal.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen","170671 ; 170675 ; 170676 ; 170677","2018-09-13T09:11:07.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968307/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968307/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968307/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-05","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the effect on wages of the UK leaving the EU without a deal; and if he will place a copy of that assessment in the Library.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","170674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968308","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-09-10","<p>​The UK is pressing the Burmese and Bangladeshi governments to work together to create the conditions for the safe, voluntary and dignified return of the Rohingya to Burma. The Foreign Secretary intends to visit Burma and convene a meeting at the UN General Assembly to galvanise international support for this process. In their conversation on 17 August, I called on Burma's Minister for International Cooperation to ensure that UNDP and UNHCR representatives are given unfettered access to northern Rakhine – a key element of the agreement reached by Burma and the UN in June.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-09-10T16:25:16.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968308/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968308/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968308/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-09-05","Rohingya: Repatriation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant the oral answer to the hon Member for Liverpool, West Derby on 4 September 2018, Official Report, column 5, what steps his Department are taking to enable the safe return of the Rohingya to their home.","false","Biography information for Preet Kaur Gill","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Preet Kaur Gill","170890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968309","Department for International Development","false","2018-09-10","<p>During her recent visit to Africa, the Prime Minister set out plans for a new long-term UK partnership with African nations. She announced a number of measures to increase the impact and effectiveness of UK aid across Africa, including to help our partners meet the poverty challenges of the future by: harnessing the power of trade, investment and business to create jobs; tackling the causes of extremism, instability and poverty; and addressing opportunities and challenges brought about by climate change and demographic shifts.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-09-10T15:57:54.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968309/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968309/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968309/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-09-05","Africa: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment her Department has made of the effect of the Government’s strategic shift on UK aid on poverty reduction in Africa.","false","Biography information for Preet Kaur Gill","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Preet Kaur Gill","170891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968310","Treasury","false","2018-09-13","<p>The Government has published its White Paper on the future relationship, which is our vision for a bold, ambitious and innovative new partnership with the EU.</p><p> </p><p>The Government remains confident the UK and EU will agree a mutually advantageous deal. Leaving the EU without a deal is in neither side’s interests.</p><p> </p><p>Once the Government has agreed a deal with the EU we will provide Parliament with the appropriate analysis of that deal ahead of the vote on the final deal.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen","170671 ; 170674 ; 170676 ; 170677","2018-09-13T09:11:07.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968310/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968310/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968310/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-05","Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the amount of revenue required through (a) income tax or (b) corporation tax to offset the £80 billion of additional borrowing forecast in his letter to the Treasury Committee relating to Brexit analysis, dated 23 August 2018; and if he will place a copy of the findings in the Library.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","170675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968311","Treasury","false","2018-09-14","<p>The charge on disguised remuneration (DR) loans is targeted at artificial tax avoidance schemes where earnings were paid in the form of non-repayable loans, often made by an offshore third party.</p><p> </p><p>It is unfair to ordinary taxpayers to let anybody continue to benefit from contrived tax avoidance of this sort, and that is why this government has taken action to ensure that everybody pays the taxes they owe.</p><p> </p><p>As the charge on DR loans is specifically targeted at these contrived tax avoidance schemes it is not expected to have a significant effect on the NHS.</p><p> </p><p>For more information please see the issue briefing, published in July 2018: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/hmrc-issue-briefing-disguised-remuneration-charge-on-loans</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-09-14T11:34:12.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968311/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968311/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968311/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-05","Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment his Department has made of the effect the 2019 Loan Charge on the NHS.","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","170892"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968312","Treasury","false","2018-09-14","<p>Where agency health workers are directly engaged by the Trusts, then VAT is due on the introductory fee charged by the agency.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC review the VAT position of all taxpayers, including NHS trusts, to help ensure that VAT is collected where it is due.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-09-14T11:24:51.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968312/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968312/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968312/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-05","NHS: Agency Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an estimate of the VAT loss to the public purse of the use of direct engagement models for agency health workers in the NHS.","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","170893"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968313","Cabinet Office","false","2018-09-14","<p>The Access to Elections Working Group is appropriately resourced.</p><p> </p><p>We received over 250 responses from the Call for evidence and have published a report of key findings and actions to be taken forward for polls reserved to the UK Government to ensure that our elections are as accessible as possible, and to remove any barriers that exist to democratic participation.</p><p> </p><p>Implementation of the action is split between disabled people's’ organisations (in widening awareness), Government (in any potential legislative change), the Electoral Commission (in revision and development of guidance) and Returning Officers (in training of staff and running of polls).</p><p> </p><p>The Group’s membership includes leading charities and key electoral stakeholders who will work together to better support disabled people’s participation in our democratic process.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2018-09-14T11:11:35.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968313/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968313/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968313/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-09-05","Elections: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that the access to elections working group is appropriately resourced to implement the actions set out in the Government's response to Call for evidence: access to elections, published in August 2018.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","170894"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968314","Department for International Development","false","2018-09-10","<p>The UK Government is very concerned by the growing humanitarian crisis in Venezuela and the region. The UK is already providing support to the crisis through our core funding to key UN humanitarian agencies and the Red Cross Movement, and DFID will shortly be deploying two humanitarian advisors to the region to explore how best we may complement international humanitarian aid efforts within Venezuela and the wider region.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-09-10T17:01:29.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968314/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968314/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968314/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-09-05","Venezuela: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what support the Government provides to Venezuelan refugees living in other Latin American countries.","false","Biography information for Preet Kaur Gill","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Preet Kaur Gill","170895"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968315","Cabinet Office","false","2018-09-10","<p>The Government received the reports of the four Boundary Commissions on 5 September 2018 and we expect that the reports will be laid before Parliament and made publicly available on Monday 10 September 2018 to allow for the reports to be printed.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2018-09-10T15:36:44.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968315/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968315/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968315/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-09-05","Constituencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, when the Government plans to lay the Boundary Commission's recommendations before the House.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","170709"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968317","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-09-10","<p>As at 31 August 2018, the complement of the Ministry of Defence Police (MDP) was 2,800 deployed at 53 locations across the UK and Northern Ireland, the details of which I am withholding on grounds of safeguarding national security. The MDP's senior Command Structure is comprised of the Chief Constable, Deputy Chief Constable, Senior Civil Service 1star and two Assistant Chief Constables. These officers are located at the force HQ, Wethersfield, Essex.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-09-10T15:32:54.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968317/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968317/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968317/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-09-05","Ministry of Defence Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the establishment and command structure by rank of the Ministry of Defence Police is; and at what locations they are deployed.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","170656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968318","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-09-17","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy currently has approximately 300 staff working outside greater London.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy does not occupy St Paul’s Place Sheffield and has had no staff based at that location since July 2018.</p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2018-09-17T15:23:04.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968318/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968318/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968318/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-09-05","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many and what proportion of his Department's staff are based in his Department's Sheffield office at St Paul’s place.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","170896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968319","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-09-10","<p>We continue to urge the DPRK to uphold its human rights obligations and engage substantively with the international community on freedom of religion in North Korea. We work with partners in international fora, such as the UN General Assembly and Human Rights Council, to highlight this and other human rights concerns. We raise our concerns directly with the North Korean Embassy in London and through our Embassy in Pyongyang. We also regularly engage with NGOs on human rights issues in the DPRK.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-09-10T16:14:40.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968319/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968319/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968319/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-09-05","North Korea: Christianity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to help tackle the persecution of Christians in North Korea.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","170717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968320","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-09-10","<p>We are currently carefully considering the findings and recommendations made in the Child Migration Programmes report by the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse (IICSA) and will respond in due course.</p><p> </p><p>We are aware of the age and declining health of many former child migrants, and we are committed to providing a considered response to all of the Inquiry's recommendations. The Home Office leads on the Government's response to the IICSA Interim Report.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","170887","2018-09-10T15:58:46.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968320/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968320/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968320/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-09-05","Child Sexual Abuse Independent Panel Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Mental Health and Inequalities of 3 July 2018, Official Report, column 105WH, for what reason his Department did not publish before the summer parliamentary recess a formal response to the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse's report on Child Migrant Programmes, published on 1 March 2018.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","170897"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968322","Home Office","false","2018-09-10","<p>The UK has decided, as a matter of domestic policy, that the main requirement for eligibility under the EU Settlement Scheme will be continuous residence in the UK.</p><p>We will accept a wide range of documentation as proof of residence. Where possible, the application process will help the applicant to establish their continuous residence and whether it amounts to five years, on an automated basis using data held by HM Revenue &amp; Customs (HMRC) and in due course also the Department for Work and Pensions (DWP). The latter may include data on receipt of state retirement pension.</p><p>Being in receipt of a state retirement pension may help the applicant to prove their residency, but receipt of public funds in any form will not affect the applicant’s eligibility for the EU Settlement Scheme.</p><p>The requirement for five years’ continuous residence can be satisfied by any such period of time during an applicant’s life in the UK rather than the most recent five years, provided it began before 31 December 2020. However, the applicant must not have been absent from the UK for more than five continuous years since that period ended.</p><p>EU citizens and their family members who obtain settled status will be granted indefinite leave to remain (ILR) in the UK. This status will provide the holder with the same access to benefits, education and healthcare as those who acquire permanent residence under EU law.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","170899 ; 170900 ; 170901","2018-09-10T16:30:08.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968322/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968322/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968322/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-09-05","Immigration: State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether it is his policy for an application for settled status to be affected by the applicant being in receipt of a state retirement pension.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","170898"
