icy that the five-year continuous residency requirement for settled status can be satisfied by reference to any such period of time during an applicant’s life in the UK rather than the most recent five years.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","170900"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968325","Home Office","false","2018-09-10","<p>The UK has decided, as a matter of domestic policy, that the main requirement for eligibility under the EU Settlement Scheme will be continuous residence in the UK.</p><p>We will accept a wide range of documentation as proof of residence. Where possible, the application process will help the applicant to establish their continuous residence and whether it amounts to five years, on an automated basis using data held by HM Revenue &amp; Customs (HMRC) and in due course also the Department for Work and Pensions (DWP). The latter may include data on receipt of state retirement pension.</p><p>Being in receipt of a state retirement pension may help the applicant to prove their residency, but receipt of public funds in any form will not affect the applicant’s eligibility for the EU Settlement Scheme.</p><p>The requirement for five years’ continuous residence can be satisfied by any such period of time during an applicant’s life in the UK rather than the most recent five years, provided it began before 31 December 2020. However, the applicant must not have been absent from the UK for more than five continuous years since that period ended.</p><p>EU citizens and their family members who obtain settled status will be granted indefinite leave to remain (ILR) in the UK. This status will provide the holder with the same access to benefits, education and healthcare as those who acquire permanent residence under EU law.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","170898 ; 170899 ; 170900","2018-09-10T16:30:09.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968325/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968325/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968325/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-09-05","EU Nationals: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether people who have settled status will continue to be able to access the NHS after the UK leaves the EU on the same basis as EU citizens can today.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","170901"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968326","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-09-14","<p>Over the past months, UK Government Ministers and officials have met a range of stakeholders in Northern Ireland, including representatives of political parties, and made clear that while we are confident that we will agree a deal with the European Union, which remains by far the most likely outcome, it is the responsibility of the Government to continue preparations for the full range of potential outcomes, including no deal. As we do, and as decisions are made, we will take full account of the unique circumstances of Northern Ireland.</p><p>In the event there was no deal, the UK Government is clear that we must respect our unique relationship with Ireland, with whom we share a land border and who are co-signatories of the Belfast Agreement. The UK Government has consistently placed upholding the Agreement and its successors at the heart of our approach and we will continue to do so while safeguarding the integrity of the United Kingdom and respecting the principle of consent.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2018-09-14T12:50:13.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968326/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968326/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968326/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-09-05","Brexit: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether he has had discussions with the leaders of the political parties in Northern Ireland on the Government’s plan for Northern Ireland in the event that the UK leaves the EU without a deal.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","170740"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968328","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-09-21","<p>We are working at pace with the European Commission to secure a future relationship that meets in full the commitments we made in the December Joint Report on Northern Ireland. This is reflected fully in our White Paper proposals, which would avoid a hard border, preserve the integrity of the UK internal market and Northern Ireland’s place within it, and preserve North-South cooperation in line with the Belfast Agreement.</p><p>It is rightly the priority on all sides that those issues should be resolved through our future partnership. But we remain absolutely committed to agreeing a legally operative backstop in the Withdrawal Agreement alongside a framework for that future relationship. We have already agreed legal text with the EU on maintaining the Common Travel Area and associated rights and on protecting North-South cooperation. We have put forward an alternative proposal on the customs elements of the backstop, the Temporary Customs Arrangement, that would only come into force in specific and narrow circumstances. We are now intensifying discussions on both fronts as we look ahead to reaching agreement in the autumn.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2018-09-21T11:23:37.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968328/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968328/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968328/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-09-05","Borders: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what progress he has made with his counterparts in the EU on the prevention of a hard border between Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland as a result of the UK leaving the EU without remaining in (a) a customs union or (b) the single market.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","170741"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968329","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-09-14","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union now has over 650 staff based in the UK plus the expertise of over 120 officials in Brussels working on EU exit work.</p><p>The Department continues to recruit the brightest and the best from across the civil service, the wider public sector and the private sector. We regularly review headcount to ensure we are appropriately resourced to deliver the Department’s objectives to secure the best possible deal on the United Kingdom’s departure from the EU; and build a deep and comprehensive future partnership between the UK and the EU.</p><p> </p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris",,"2018-09-14T12:39:31.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968329/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968329/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968329/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-09-05","Department for Exiting the European Union: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many civil servants are working on his Department's papers to prepare for the UK leaving the EU without a deal.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","170742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968330","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-09-13","<p>The Secretary of State meets regularly with Michel Barnier to discuss the issues related to our exit.</p><p>We are discussing all of the issues set out in the White Paper with the EU and have said that we want to enable UK and EU tourists to continue to travel visa-free in the future, maintaining the close links between our people.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2018-09-13T15:15:18.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968330/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968330/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968330/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-09-05","Travel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what recent discussions he has had with his EU counterparts on travel requirements for EU and UK holiday-makers after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","170743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968331","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-09-14","<p>On 8 March, the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland set out a NI budget position for 2018-19 to give clarity and certainty on NI finances for the year ahead. It provides a secure basis for protecting and preserving public services including in education which has seen spending protected in real terms for the 2018/19 financial year.</p><p>Education is a devolved matter and while we have ensured that sufficient funding has been provided to maintain the overall schools budget at the same level as 2017-18, decisions on the allocation of that budget and the associated assessment of the financial position of individual schools are a matter for the Department of Education, and in the absence of the Executive, the Department’s Permanent Secretary.</p><p>The Secretary of State and I remain firmly of the belief that the right way forward for decision making in Northern Ireland on critical issues such as the funding of schools lies in stable, fully functioning and inclusive devolved government and working towards restoring devolved government remains our top priority.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2018-09-14T13:16:31.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968331/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968331/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968331/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-09-05","Schools: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what estimate he has made of the number of schools in Northern Ireland that are in a financial deficit.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","170744"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968332","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-09-10","<p>Northern Ireland has proven itself to be a top destination for foreign direct investment, with over 900 international companies investing in Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State for Northern Ireland and I regularly champion new investment announcements in Northern Ireland, which show that Northern Ireland continues to be a great place to invest and do business, and the Secretary of State was present at the announcement by PA Consulting that they will be creating 400 new jobs in Belfast over the next five years.</p><p> </p><p>We are working to restore a stable, devolved government which can work with the UK Government to maximise Northern Ireland’s attractiveness to overseas investors.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2018-09-10T09:40:03.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968332/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968332/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968332/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-09-05","Foreign Investment in UK: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what steps she is taking to ensure that foreign investment in Northern Ireland continues.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","170745"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968334","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-09-10","<p>The Northern Ireland Office is involved in the planning of Decade of Centenaries commemorations in Northern Ireland, but does not yet have plans to commemorate the centenary of the creation of Northern Ireland in 2021.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State and I will continue to work with all the NI parties, and with the Irish Government as appropriate, to remove the barriers to restoring the Executive and a fully functioning Assembly, leading to restored local planning and decision-making on issues such as the commemoration of this centenary.</p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2018-09-10T09:41:29.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968334/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968334/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968334/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-09-05","Anniversaries: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, whether her Department plans to commemorate in 2021 the centenary of the creation of Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","170746"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968335","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-09-13","<p>In the absence of the Executive, the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland continues to engage with political leaders and representatives across Northern Ireland’s health sector to discuss key health challenges and priorities including the implementation of the Bengoa recommendations.</p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2018-09-13T11:11:45.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968335/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968335/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968335/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-09-05","Health Services: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what discussions she has had with political leaders in Northern Ireland on implementing the recommendations of the Bengoa report.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","170747"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968336","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-09-13","<p>The Secretary of State for Northern Ireland holds regular discussions with the Northern Ireland Civil Service on a range of pressing issues. This is a devolved matter but we are assured that appropriate action is taken to ensure fire safety checks are carried out regularly on buildings which pose the greatest risk to public safety as this is a statutory requirement.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2018-09-13T15:12:14.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968336/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968336/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968336/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-09-05","Listed Buildings: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what discussions she plans to hold with the Northern Ireland administration on ensuring the adequacy of fire safety checks of listed buildings as a result of the fire at Bank Buildings in Belfast.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","170748"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968337","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-09-12","<p>The Government published the Agriculture Bill on 12 September 2018.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-09-12T14:57:24.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968337/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968337/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968337/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-09-05","Agriculture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when his Department plans to publish the draft Agricultural Bill.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","170749"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968338","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-09-14","<p>The UK State Pension will remain payable worldwide under domestic legislation following our departure from the EU.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-09-14T13:48:08.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968338/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968338/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968338/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-09-05","Pensioners: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps she is taking to ensure that British citizens receiving a UK pension while living elsewhere in the EU continue to receive that pension after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","170750"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968339","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-09-14","<p>Research carried out by the National Federation of ALMOs shows over three quarters of their tenants come onto Universal Credit with pre-existing rent arrears.</p><p>Arrears are usually temporary and the majority of claimants do succeed in paying their rent, managing their monthly payments and clearing their arrears over time. However, this year following the Autumn 2017 Budget, we have abolished waiting days and now provide 2 weeks of extra housing support to claimants moving to Universal Credit from Housing Benefit.</p><p>The assessment period and payment structure of Universal Credit is integral to the overall design, which requires an assessment period of a month to assess earnings. Support is available in the first assessment period through the system of advances. We have also made changes to improve advances, and they can now be repaid over a course of 12 months and can consist of up to 100 per cent of the indicative monthly award from day one.</p><p> </p><p>Around 80 per cent of new claims are paid in full and on time. In many cases where full payment is not made on time, it is due to unresolved issues such as: claimants not accepting their Claimant Commitment or passing identity checks, or having outstanding verification issues, such as housing costs and self-employed earnings. Whilst their verification is on-going, many claimants receive a part payment for those elements of the claim that have been resolved.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-09-14T14:21:38.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968339/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968339/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968339/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-09-05","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether she plans to reduce waiting times for payments of universal credit to help ensure that tenants do not fall into rent arrears.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","170751"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968340","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-09-11","<p>The vast majority of employers are meeting their responsibilities under automatic enrolment, consistent with the legal framework established under the Pensions Act 2008. Where employers fail to comply with the law however, The Pensions Regulator (TPR) has a full range of powers to ensure workers get the pensions they are due.</p><p> </p><p>TPR publishes a quarterly bulletin on automatic enrolment compliance and enforcement activities on its website, the latest update can be found here: <a href="http://www.thepensionsregulator.gov.uk/docs/compliance-and-enforcement-quarterly-bulletin-april-to-june-2018.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.thepensionsregulator.gov.uk/docs/compliance-and-enforcement-quarterly-bulletin-april-to-june-2018.pdf</a></p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2018-09-11T16:18:22.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968340/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968340/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968340/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-09-05","Occupational Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate she has made of the number of employers who have been identified as not providing a workplace pension scheme.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","170752"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968341","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-09-19","<p>Transitional Protection will not be awarded for a fixed period, but will remain in place until the underlying Universal Credit entitlement increases, which will bring claimants’ entitlement into line with that of those making new claims. Transitional Protection will end, however, if the claimant has a significant change of circumstance.</p><p> </p><p>Subject to Parliament approving the necessary legislation, which we have announced will be brought forward in the autumn, we will be starting managed migration of existing benefit claimants to Universal Credit in 2019 and plan to complete this process in 2023. It is estimated this legislation will bring in £2.6 billion of transitional protection by 2023 (OBR Welfare Trends report January 2018) boosting the incomes of around 1 million Universal Credit households. The regulations also include additional transitional protection arrangements for all approximately 500,000 claimants eligible for a Severe Disability Premium.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-09-19T14:42:24.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968341/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968341/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968341/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-09-05","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the planned timescale is for the transitional protection period for universal credit.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","170753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968342","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-09-13","<p>In the financial year April 2017 to March 2018, 29% of all PIP face to face assessments were conducted in the Claimants home.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-09-13T13:43:47.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968342/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968342/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968342/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-09-05","Personal Independence Payment: Medical Examinations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of personal independence payments assessments are home visits.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","170754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968344","Department for Transport","false","2018-09-13","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency (DVSA) are responsible for enforcing the drivers’ hours rules. In 2017, in England, Scotland and Wales (for the period 1st January to 31st December), DVSA issued 482 fixed penalty notices and 120 prosecutions that resulted in a fine, for exceeding drivers’ hours limits. During the course of this period a given driver could have been issued with more than one fine.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-09-13T15:55:45.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968344/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968344/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968344/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-09-05","Large Goods Vehicle Drivers: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many lorry drivers were fined for driving over their allotted time limits in 2017.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","170755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968345","Treasury","false","2018-09-14","<p>HMRC allocates resource in a flexible manner to manage emerging pressures by identifying savings and reallocating resources within its overall allocations set by the Treasury. Information on the structure and organisation of HM Revenue and Customs is available at</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/hmrc-annual-report-and-accounts-2017-to-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/hmrc-annual-report-and-accounts-2017-to-2018</a></p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-09-14T10:26:00.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968345/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968345/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968345/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-05","Child Trust Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what additional resources he is allocating to HMRC to assist parents in locating lost Child Trust Fund accounts.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","170710"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968346","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-09-10","<p>The Government is committed to tackling fly-tipping on a number of fronts. In 2015 we gave local authorities stronger powers to stop, search and seize vehicles of those suspected of fly-tipping. It is the responsibility of local authorities to use the powers available to them and we encourage them to do so when appropriate and proportionate. We are adding to these powers and have consulted this year on a new fixed penalty notice for householders who pass their waste to a fly-tipper. The National Fly-tipping Prevention Group has published guidance which sets out clearly the powers available to local authorities and other partners when tackling fly-tipping.</p><p> </p><p>The powers were enhanced in March 2015 and the data available since then shows a total of 326 vehicles seized by local authorities in England. 197 vehicles were seized in 2016/17, a 52% increase from 129 vehicles seized in 2015/16. The statistics for 2017/18 are due to be published in October. National fly-tipping statistics are available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fly-tipping-in-england" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fly-tipping-in-england</a>.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","170712","2018-09-10T10:26:31.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968346/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968346/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968346/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-09-05","Fly-tipping","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps he is taking to encourage local authorities to use the powers available to them to seize vehicles used in fly-tipping activities; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","170711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968347","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-09-10","<p>The Government is committed to tackling fly-tipping on a number of fronts. In 2015 we gave local authorities stronger powers to stop, search and seize vehicles of those suspected of fly-tipping. It is the responsibility of local authorities to use the powers available to them and we encourage them to do so when appropriate and proportionate. We are adding to these powers and have consulted this year on a new fixed penalty notice for householders who pass their waste to a fly-tipper. The National Fly-tipping Prevention Group has published guidance which sets out clearly the powers available to local authorities and other partners when tackling fly-tipping.</p><p> </p><p>The powers were enhanced in March 2015 and the data available since then shows a total of 326 vehicles seized by local authorities in England. 197 vehicles were seized in 2016/17, a 52% increase from 129 vehicles seized in 2015/16. The statistics for 2017/18 are due to be published in October. National fly-tipping statistics are available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fly-tipping-in-england" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fly-tipping-in-england</a>.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","170711","2018-09-10T10:26:31.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968347/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968347/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968347/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-09-05","Fly-tipping","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many vehicles have been seized because of their being used in fly-tipping activities since that power was introduced; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","170712"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968348","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-09-10","<p>Endemic diseases like porcine reproductive and respiratory syndrome affect animal health and welfare, as well as productivity. As set out in our 25 Year Environment Plan and the consultation <em>Health and Harmony, the future for food, farming and the environment in a Green Brexit, </em>Defra is working with the livestock industry to reduce significantly the impact of these endemic diseases. We are analysing consultation responses and developing proposals.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-09-10T12:38:39.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968348/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968348/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968348/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-09-05","Porcine Reproductive and Respiratory Syndrome","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps he is taking to reduce the incidence of porcine reproductive respiratory syndrome; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","170713"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968349","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-09-10","<p>The Food Standard Agency’s (FSA's) understanding of meat species substitution is derived from sampling data submitted by local authorities to the United Kingdom Food Surveillance System. Whilst these data indicate the presence of substitution they are inconclusive as to the prevalence of this practice across the wider industry.</p><p>The FSA collects data annually from local authorities regarding the number of prosecutions they have taken. We do not collect information on the specific details of the individual cases.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-09-10T17:06:05.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968349/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968349/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968349/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-09-05","Meat: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of the prevalence of meat fraud whereby expensive meat is replaced with a cheaper product; and how many successful prosecutions there have been for such offences in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","170714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968350","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-09-10","<p>The Government has no plans to alter or repeal the ban on farmers feeding human food waste to pigs. It is already possible to feed pigs certain food waste originating from food producers, manufacturers and retailers, provided they comprise no prohibited animal by-products. However, the ban on feeding catering waste to pigs needs to stay in place as it can present a serious risk to animal health and has been directly responsible for major notifiable disease outbreaks around the world, including the 2001 foot and mouth disease outbreak in the UK.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-09-10T12:50:05.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968350/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968350/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968350/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-09-05","Animal Feed: Pigs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether he plans to alter or repeal the ban on farmers feeding human food waste to pigs; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","170715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968351","Scotland Office","false","2018-09-10","<p>My officials continue to engage with the Islands Councils in order to understand their aspirations for a Deal.</p><p> </p><p>We have either agreed a Deal or have agreed to negotiate a Deal, for each of Scotland’s seven cities, along with Ayrshire and our Borderlands. This amounts to a commitment so far of over £1 billion to support economic growth across Scotland. In consultation with HM Treasury, I hope to agree commitments to further Deals in due course.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2018-09-10T15:08:20.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968351/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968351/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968351/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2018-09-05","Scottish Islands: Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what progress the UK Government has made on an islands' deal; and when the Government plans to publish details on that deal.","false","Biography information for Lesley Laird","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Lesley Laird","170902"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968352","Cabinet Office","false","2018-09-10","<p>The Cabinet Office is responsible for the settlement of election expenses claims in respect of constituencies in England and Wales. Data for constituencies in Northern Ireland and Scotland is not available to the Cabinet Office at present.</p><p> </p><p>The number of claims that exceeded the maximum recoverable amount in England and Wales at the 2017 UK parliamentary general election was 236. This is 41% of the claims for consideration by the Cabinet Office. The Elections Claims Unit at the Cabinet Office is scrutinising these claims to ensure that the expenses claimed were reasonable and necessary for the efficient and effective delivery of the poll as is required by law. This could result in some claims being settled at an amount that is less than originally claimed and below the maximum recoverable amount for that constituency and therefore the overall number of claims that are over spent could change.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2018-09-10T15:44:10.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968352/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968352/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968352/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-09-05","General Election 2017: Returning Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many and what proportion of returning officers spent in excess of their maximum recoverable amount at the 2017 general election.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","170903"
